<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="231" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[140,1108,166,897]" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[185,312,166,192]" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis box="[185,307,166,192]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Within 
<collectingCountry box="[417,573,167,193]" name="United States of America" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">United States</collectingCountry>
the boldly streaked orange and blackish-gray forewing pattern of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[370,563,202,228]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferricola">
<emphasis box="[370,563,202,228]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Hypotrix ferricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unmistakable. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[766,959,202,228]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferricola">
<emphasis box="[766,959,202,228]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Hypotrix ferricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Dyar, 1916)" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Dyar" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[239,593,237,264]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aselenographa" status="comb. n.">
<emphasis box="[239,261,238,263]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[280,428,237,263]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">aselenographa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dyar HG" box="[447,584,237,264]" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" pagination="1 - 37" refId="ref13742" refString="Dyar HG (1916) Descriptions of new Lepidoptera from Mexico. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 51: 1 - 37." type="journal article" year="1916">Dyar, 1916</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[608,712,237,264]" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" rank="species">comb. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
[
<taxonomicName authority="Dyar, 1916" authorityName="Dyar" authorityYear="1916" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Trichorthosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aselenographa">
<emphasis box="[732,1033,237,263]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Trichorthosia aselenographa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Dyar HG" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" pagination="1 - 37" refId="ref13742" refString="Dyar HG (1916) Descriptions of new Lepidoptera from Mexico. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 51: 1 - 37." type="journal article" year="1916">Dyar, 1916</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
] from 
<collectingCountry box="[280,367,272,298]" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, except the subterminal line in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[727,853,272,299]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferricola">
<emphasis box="[727,749,273,298]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[765,853,272,298]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">ferricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is parallel to the wing margin in the middle part of the wing and then curves outward near the forewing apex (the subterminal line is almost straight to the forewing apex in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dyar" authorityYear="1916" box="[879,1066,343,369]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Trichorthosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aselenographa">
<emphasis box="[879,901,343,368]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[918,1066,343,369]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">aselenographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, so the terminal area is broad mesially and tapered toward each end), and the dark patch in the cell through the reniform and orbicular spots is paler, so the orbicular spot is evident as a dark streak and the reniform spot as a dark crescent (the streak in the cell in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dyar" authorityYear="1916" box="[171,358,483,510]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Trichorthosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aselenographa">
<emphasis box="[171,193,484,509]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[210,358,483,509]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">aselenographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is black, completely obscuring the reniform and orbicular spots). The forewing length in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[409,535,519,545]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferricola">
<emphasis box="[409,431,519,544]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[447,535,519,545]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">ferricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<quantity box="[569,725,518,545]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" unit="mm" value="14.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="13.0">13 to 15 mm</quantity>
. The 
<emphasis box="[788,942,519,545]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">male genitalia</emphasis>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[981,1107,519,545]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferricola">
<emphasis box="[981,1003,519,544]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1019,1107,519,545]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">ferricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a small, triangular, heavily sclerotized cucullus with a stout seta at the anal angle, a rounded U-shaped notch in the ventral margin of the valve anterior to the cucullus, an apically spatulate uncus, and a long, slender digitus. Th e vesica is very long and narrow with a dense band of spinules on the apical half, a stout rose-thorn spine at the base, and a field of six or seven spike-like cornuti subbasally. In the 
<emphasis box="[840,1011,695,721]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">female genitalia</emphasis>
the corpus bursae is rounded and the appendix bursae is long and narrow and gently coiled.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="231" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[140,1108,166,897]" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[185,504,765,791]" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis box="[185,336,765,791]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" reason="1">Distribution</emphasis>
and biology.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[519,718,765,791]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferricola">
<emphasis box="[519,718,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Hypotrix ferricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in southeastern Arizona, southwestern New 
<collectingRegion box="[361,448,800,826]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Mexico</collectingRegion>
, and northern 
<collectingCountry box="[624,711,800,826]" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. Collecting dates range from early April to early August, possibly representing several generations. Most records are from ponderosa pine forests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
